			<article class="post-2099 post type-post status-publish hentry category-dealbook" id="post-2099">
                        <div class="visually-hidden">
                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: Blame Game in Apple Pay Fraud</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By Sydney Ember                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-03-17T11:08:16+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">March 17, 2015 7:08 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">March 17, 2015 7:08 am</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/03/17/morning-agenda-blame-game-in-apple-pay-fraud/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Blame Game in Apple Pay Fraud" data-description="Banks and Apple Pay tussle over fraud. | Valeant wins the bidding war for Salix. | Pinterest garners $11 billion valuation. | Troops come home to repossessions.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>BLAME GAME IN APPLE PAY FRAUD</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> When Apple was planning its Apple Pay electronic payment system last summer for its iPhones, the nationâs banks rushed to be included. Now, some of the banks âare privately complaining that Apple Pay may not be so great after all,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/17/business/banks-find-fraud-abounds-in-apple-pay.html?ref=dealbook">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column</a>. âBut the banks may largely have themselves to blame,â he adds. âA raft of headlines over the last week about unusually high fraud rates from thieves using stolen credit numbers on Apple Pay has exposed what many of the banks privately acknowledge they have been trying to fix for months.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Itâs not clear whether Apple is entirely to blame. âMore likely <b>it is at least as much the banksâ fault</b>, if not more,â Mr. Sorkin writes. Apple Pay should in general cut down on fraud, but the systemâs vulnerability is in the way that it, and card issuers, âonboardâ new credit cards onto the system. And the banks, which were eager to become the customersâ default card on Apple Pay, did little to build their own defenses or to push Apple to provide more detailed information about its customers, Mr. Sorkin adds. What is more, it seems that banks directed users whose cards were flagged to a customer care phone center, not a fraud prevention center. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAll of this has led to a <b>thriving black market</b> in which thieves enter stolen credit card numbers into iPhones, essentially turning the devices into physical credit cards, which they in turn take to stores and walk out with merchandise. Thieves have even used Apple Pay at Apple Stores,â Mr. Sorkin writes. âFirst-mover advantage is often crucial when it comes to the rapidly changing and rabidly competitive world of technology, but that can quickly turn to disadvantage when companies rush headlong into trouble.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>LOFTY VALUATION FOR PINTEREST</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Pinterest, an online scrapbooking service, disclosed on Monday that it had raised about $367 million in a new round of financing from new and existing investors, giving it a valuation of $11 billion, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/17/business/dealbook/pinterest-valuation-at-11-billion-after-new-round-of-fund-raising.html?ref=dealbook">DealBookâs Michael J. de la Merced reports</a>. In a regulatory filing, Pinterest disclosed that it could raise as much as $211 million in additional financing, bringing its potential haul to $578 million. That would be on top of the $764 million that the nearly five-year-old start-up has raised in previous rounds.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe latest round highlights the investment worldâs <b>continuing infatuation with Pinterest</b>,â Mr. de la Merced writes. Existing investors include the venture capital firms Andreessen Horowitz and Bessemer Venture Partners, and the Japanese e-commerce company Rakuten. The start-up has nearly tripled its valuation in just about a year and a half.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>VALEANT WINS BATTLE FOR SALIX</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Valeant Pharmaceuticals International, which failed in its bid for Allergan last year, increased its bid for Salix Pharmaceuticals on Monday, ending a bidding war with Endo International, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/17/business/dealbook/valeant-raises-offer-for-salix.html?ref=dealbook">DealBookâs David Gelles writes</a>. Valeant said it would now pay about $11 billion, or $173 a share for Salix, which makes gastrointestinal drugs, from its previous offer of $158 a share. The increase of about 9 percent amounts to an additional $1 billion for Salix shareholders, and the boards of both companies approved the revised deal over the weekend. The termination fee that would be payable by Salix to Valeant has been increased by $100 million, to $456 million.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Shortly after the revised agreement was announced, Endo said it was withdrawing its $11.2 billion proposal to acquire Salix. Valeant must now come up with $11 billion in cash. To help finance its offer, Valeant will <b>issue $1.45 billion in new shares.</b> This will allow the company to pay for the deal without taking on more debt from banks, which could have damaged its credit rating, Mr. Gelles writes. William A. Ackman, who runs the hedge fund Pershing Square Capital Management, took a roughly 5 percent stake in Valeant this year, saying he would be a passive investor, and was prepared to help the company finance a bid for Salix.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The <b>Federal Reserveâs policy-making committee</b> convenes for its two-day meeting. Monthly data on <b>housing starts</b> is out at 8:30 a.m. <b>Mary Jo White</b>, the chairwoman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, gives a speech at the Securities Industry and Financial Markets Association Compliance and Legal Society Annual Seminar in Phoenix.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>On the Hill</b>: The <b>House Financial Services Committee</b> holds a hearing titled âThe Annual Testimony of the Secretary of the Treasury on the State of the International Financial Systemâ at 10 a.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>TROOPS COME HOME TO REPOSSESSIONS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Many Americans are contractually obligated to resolve their disputes with investment advisers or lenders through mandatory arbitration. It is supposed to be different for deployed service members, who are to have been given a number of protections from repossessions and foreclosures, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/17/business/wronged-troops-are-denied-recourse-by-arbitration-clauses.html?ref=dealbook">Jessica Silver-Greenberg and Michael Corkery write in DealBook</a>. But efforts to maintain that special status for service members have run into resistance from the financial industry, including many of the same banks that promote the work they do for veterans.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Through the use of mandatory arbitration, some companies repeatedly <b>violate the federal protections</b>, leaving troops and their families vulnerable to predatory lending, military lawyers and government officials say. Last year, a bipartisan bill that would have allowed service members to opt out of arbitration and file a lawsuit met with opposition from the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and Wall Streetâs major trade group, the Securities Industry and Financial Markets Association, or Sifma. The trade groupsâ members include financial companies that have trumpeted their hiring of veterans and their initiatives for troops returning home from war, including JPMorgan Chase and USAA.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many banks contend that <b>arbitration is a more efficient</b> and less costly way to handle disputes, Ms. Silver-Greenberg and Mr. Corkery write. The clauses clamp down on frivolous litigation, including class-action lawsuits, and the cost savings allow companies to provide more affordable products to consumers, the trade organizations say. Consumer lawyers say it is easy to understand why the industry is lobbying against an exemption for service members: One carve-out from mandatory arbitration could bolster broader calls to excise the clauses from contracts altogether.</p>
</div>
